Software Engineer - React Prep Guide

Please read this guide in its entirety before starting the scenarios, especially the parts in bold. You'll find helpful tips on how to prepare that will maximize your chances of success.

Our goal with these scenarios is to get insight into how you solve the kinds of real-world problems you might encounter on the job. You will not need to recall esoteric algorithms or little-used data structures. Here's what you'll work on during this 90 minute exercise:

  • Debugging a problem with limited information (25-35 minutes)
  • Determine when a user’s account may be breached (25-40 minutes)
  • Show a user when their account may be compromised (15-30 minutes)

We'll help you understand exactly what skills we're looking for and provide opportunities for you to demonstrate those skills. Not everyone will progress to an interview, but that's okay! We'll provide detailed, actionable feedback that will hopefully increase your chances of receiving an interview invitation in the future.

Time guidance

These scenarios are designed and benchmarked so that you can be successful in around 90 minutes. In this time, you get deep enough to show off your skills along multiple dimensions, but you're not competing against candidates who happen to have a lighter workload or fewer family obligations.

Although some candidates will complete these scenarios in 90 minutes or less, please plan to set aside an uninterrupted block of 120 minutes for these scenarios. This gives you a buffer in case you run into any issues or need to research anything once the timer starts.

We will provide specific time guidance for each scenario in the coding environment to make sure you are able to complete both of them.

Policies

In order to make sure everyone is on equal footing, here are some baseline policies to keep in mind:

  • You can consult books or online resources.
  • Please cite sources for any code that you pull in.
  • Please do not discuss the scenarios with other candidates.

How to prepare

Before you begin, you should plan to spend at least 30 to 60 minutes in two key areas:

  • Trying out the coding environment
  • Reviewing key concepts
Qualified

We use a platform called Qualified to deliver our scenarios in an easy-to-access online environment. We recommend that you read through our detailed Qualified guide, even if you’ve used it before.

CodeSandbox

CodeSandbox is an online javascript IDE and execution environment. CodeSandbox is preconfigured with hot module reloading, Prettier code formatting, a Jest test harness, and more to make it as easy as possible to rapidly iterate on frontend code. If you have not used CodeSandbox before, we recommend spinning up a test project and playing with it for a few minutes before you begin.

We have some answers to frequently asked questions about CodeSandbox.

Key Concepts

All of the scenarios in this work simulation will require some basic programming knowledge. Here are some of the key concepts you may want to review, especially if you are newer to programming:

  • Iteration using for loops, iterators, or functional patterns
  • Inspecting variables or lists using print statements or console logging
  • Basic knowledge of classes/objects
    • How to initialize a new object
    • How to get and set new properties
    • How to call methods on a class
  • Working with common data structures (exact terms vary by language)
    • Arrays
    • ArrayLists or vectors
    • HashMaps, maps, or dictionaries
  • Converting between different data types (string to integer, retrieving properties from a struct/Object/map, etc)

There is more specific information relating to each scenario below.



Scenarios

Debugging a problem with limited information

This scenario will involve debugging a problem based on a bug report from customer support. You will not have all of the information you need to fix the problem.

In this scenario, we are looking for things like:

  • How do you gather information about a problem in code?
  • How do you research issues?
  • How do you document your learning so others can benefit?
  • How do you communicate technical concepts to other engineers?
  • How do you communicate technical concepts to non-engineers?
Determine when a user’s account may be breached

You will modify a CodeSandbox project with some existing ES6 code. Here are some concepts you may want to review for this scenario:

  • Read and write basic JavaScript code using variables, loops, and functions
  • Work with common data structures, such as arrays and objects
  • Read and write asynchronous code in JavaScript using promises, async/await, etc
  • Make basic API calls using JavaScript’s fetch API
  • Read and write basic React code

Here are some resources that should help you prepare for the above:

JavaScript
There are no trick questions about quirky JavaScript behavior. You should be able to read and write basic ES2015 / ES6. Here's a quick reference and a deeper tutorial.

We will provide environments that are preconfigured with webpack, babel, etc throughout, so you don't need to be an expert in setting up modern JS tooling from scratch.

fetch API
You will only need to make basic GET and/or POST requests for this exercise. If you can reproduce one or two of these examples, you should be in good shape.

Show a user when their account may be compromised

You will be able to use CodeSandbox with a React/ES6 project with some existing code. Here are some concepts you may want to review for this scenario:

  • Read and write basic JavaScript code using variables, loops, and functions
  • Inspecting variables or lists using print statements or console logging
  • Work with common data structures, such as arrays and objects
  • Read and write React code

Here are some resources that should help you prepare for the above:

JavaScript
There are no trick questions about quirky JavaScript behavior. You should be able to read and write basic ES2015 / ES6. Here's a quick reference and a deeper tutorial.

We will provide environments that are preconfigured with webpack, babel, etc throughout, so you don't need to be an expert in setting up modern JS tooling from scratch.

React
This scenario does not require expert-level knowledge of React, although you should be able to read and write React at a basic level. We recommend going through the official React tutorial. If the Final Result of the tutorial looks weird and scary, that's okay! Take some time to practice and come back when you're ready.

In this scenario, we are looking for things like:

  • Does your code address the core requirements?
  • How do you manage state and pass information to components?
  • Did you handle edge cases?
  • Are your variable and function names clear?
  • How good is the overall structure of your code? (Are functions right-sized and clear? Anything that's especially hard-coded?)
  • Do you leave helpful comments explaining any tradeoffs or unclear patterns?
